<TEXT>
poachers have killed a rhinoceros seen by 
nearly every visitor to a game reserve where she had claimed a 
domain for herself and a male calf 
richard leakey the director of state wildlife management 
service said investigations were underway in the southwestern 
masai mara game reserve on the death of the black rhino nicknamed 
halima 
halima is a common name for women along kenyas indian ocean 
coast 
the animal was killed by unknown person or persons using a 
highpowered rifle said leakey in a statement monday 
leakey deplored what he called senseless killing of a well 
known tourist attraction and said halimas horn had been 
recovered 
halima who left a yearold male orphan calf permanently lived 
in a place called musiala in the game reserve and her defiance of 
migratory habits made it possible for every interested park visitor 
to see her 
rhinos are normally killed for their horn which is then ground 
into a powder that is considered an aphrodisiac in the far east 
the horn is also used to make ornate handles for daggers in persian 
gulf countries 
poachers cashing in on the demand for rhino horns have reduced 
the animals population in the east african nation from 20000 in 
the late 1970s to an estimated 400 at present most of them in 
sanctuaries 
conservationists say the slaughter of wildlife particularly 
elephants and rhinos has been reduced dramatically since leakey 
became kenyas director of wildlife management early 1988 
</TEXT>
