<TEXT>
when president bush agonizes over a difficult 
choice as hes done this week on the issue of economic sanctions 
against the soviet union he sometimes likes to quote a favorite 
philosopher yogi berra 
i love the old expression of yogi berras you say what 
happened to the mets yogi he said well we made the wrong 
mistakes the president told a group of building contractors on 
tuesday 
bush used the words of the often verbally befuddled baseball 
great to explain his decision at least for the moment not to 
slap a series of economic penalties on the soviet union in response 
to its crackdown in lithuania 
i expect in this job ill make plenty of mistakes but i dont 
want to make the wrong mistakes bush said 
once again the issue of sanctions was presenting a major 
foreign policy dilemma for bush 
just as he resisted imposing sanctions on china last year in the 
aftermath of the bloody tiananmen square massacre the president 
once again finds himself under pressure from conservatives in 
congress to act more decisively 
it was to use another favorite bush berraism deja vu all 
over again 
last summer bush finally imposed a series of noneconomic 
sanctions on the beijing government while saying he did not want 
to go further for fear of hurting the chinese people 
among those sanctions was a ban on highlevel contacts between 
governments however the president then sent national security 
adviser brent scowcroft on a secret mission to express us 
feelings about the use of force against chinas own citizens 
when confronted with the apparent violation of his own 
nocontact edict bush said he did not want to take any steps that 
would isolate china from the community of nations 
he now is making similar arguments for withholding sanctions 
against the soviet union that would show us displeasure with the 
kremlins efforts to block lithuanian independence 
administration sources said bush marched to the brink of 
announcing sanctions on moscow only to back away at least for 
the moment in response to skepticism from us allies in western 
europe over such a course and concern that us sanctions could 
only make matters worse 
explaining his reluctance bush said youve got to look at 
the real options im old enough to remember hungary in 1956 and 
where we exhorted people to go to the barricades and a lot of 
people were left out there all alone 
the president used the same argument recently for explaining why 
his administration would not formally recognize the new government 
of lithuania 
the only sanctions bush said he would consider are economic ones 
and sources say these would deal mainly with withholding trade 
and investment concessions that the united states was otherwise 
prepared to grant moscow 
economic links between the two superpowers right now are slight 
and bush has repeatedly ruled out this governments main economic 
leverage over the soviet union a grain embargo 
the bush administration and the reagan administration before 
it has argued that the trouble with economic sanctions is that 
they rarely work the way they are intended and often wind up 
hurting the wrong people 
bush voiced such an argument over past sanctions against the 
white minority rule government of south africa economic penalties 
now in place were imposed by congress over reaganbush 
administration objections 
more recently the president yielding to congressional 
pressure voiced support for keeping the sanctions in place 
against pretoria even though he disputes their value 
he has said they should remain on at least until more progress 
is made toward a oneperson onevote government 
ironically in central america where us sanctions have taken 
a major toll on national economies bush is having a hard time 
winning congressional support for undoing the impact of those 
sanctions 
vice president dan quayle heads today for the inauguration of 
nicaraguan presidentelect violeta chamorro without the aid bush 
promised her usbacked government and the new government of 
panama 
years of us economic sanctions against the leftist government 
of outgoing nicaraguan president daniel ortega and the panama 
dictatorship of manuel antonio noriega left both countries 
economies hobbled 
the presidents 800 million aid package for the two nations 
remains stalled in congress 
bush invoked the yogi berra wrong mistakes quote twice on 
tuesday after he told it to a group of agricultural writers he 
added youve got to think about that one and i dont want to 
make the wrong mistake 
</TEXT>
