drugs without more money to battle the poverty hopelessness and 
despair that fuels the drug problem 
we are fighting the war on drugs in america today in large 
part because our nation has not prevailed in the war on poverty 
houston mayor kathryn whitmire said as more than 100 mayors 
concluded a twoday meeting tuesday with police chiefs on the drug 
problem 
some democratic mayors leveled a blast at federal drug policy 
chief william bennett saying he was ignoring drug treatment 
education and poverty 
bennett told of their comments shot back some of these 
folks think leadership is coming to washington twice a year and 
complaining 
boston mayor raymond l flynn called bennett a little bit 
hypocritical for focusing on law enforcement and failing to 
address the hopelessness that drives innercity youths to drug 
abuse and the drug trade 
new york mayor david dinkins said bennett who was secretary of 
education in the reagan administration had sent exactly the 
wrong signal by suggesting drug education programs dont work 
bennetts repudiation of drug education was a cynical 
statement from the man who ran the education department through the 
era of just say no dinkins said but it was a typical 
example of the type of leadership were getting from washington 
leadership that says we have more needs and then gives us less 
their comments came a day after bennett addressed the gathering 
and encountered only gently challenging questions 
whats with these guys bennett said in an interview after 
their remarks tuesday i was there yesterday did they wait 
until i leave and then snipe at me 
bennett called dinkins remarks new york bull he said he 
had never repudiated drug education but had said that education 
alone was not sufficient to keep young people away from drugs 
the mayors issued a closing statement urging the bush 
administration to reverse itself on its opposition to providing 
federal aid directly to the cities to fight drugs rather than 
routing it through the states mayors contend states have delayed 
or kept the drug enforcement money for themselves 
the mayors said the war on drugs cannot be fought without 
addressing urban poverty joblessness and despair that encourages 
people to seek escape through drugs and makes drug dealing the 
easiest route to affluence 
whitmire said the mayors want more money for the head start 
program for disadvantaged preschoolers for job training for 
abusers and for drug treatment programs for anyone who wants it 
we can no longer conceive of winning the war unless we are 
able to offer the most basic economic opportunities to all members 
of our communities she said 
flynn at a news conference disputed bennetts assertions that 
overall drug use is down and that most drug abusers have jobs 
flynn said casual drug use may be declining but addiction and 
drugrelated violence is increasing 
the problem of drugs in this country is getting worse and 
worse flynn said its not getting better 
don hamilton bennetts press secretary responding to dinkins 
comments said federal grants to states for drug education has 
almost doubled under the bush administration from 288 million in 
1989 to a proposed 488 million for fiscal 1991 
</TEXT>
