<TEXT>
the bush administration is giving up its 
10month fight to win senate confirmation of a former civilian 
nuclear power regulator as head of the nations atomic weapons 
production 
in a letter to president bush released tuesday victor stello 
jr withdrew his name from consideration saying he believed the 
president needed to find someone who could win confirmation to the 
sensitive job at the earliest opportunity 
it has become clear to me that i cannot be that person 
stello wrote in the letter dated april 20 
greenpeace and other national environmental groups as well as 
prominent members of congress strenuously opposed stellos 
nomination they accused him of improper behavior during parts of 
his 24 years with the nuclear regulatory commission which has 
jurisdiction over civilian nuclear reactors 
stello was the nrcs chief staff official before he came to the 
energy department on temporary assignment last july after bush 
nominated him for the weapons chiefs job 
given his questionable record on health and safety issues at 
the nuclear regulatory commission victor stello should not have 
been nominated for this job in the first place sen timothy 
wirth dcolo said in response to stellos withdrawal wirth 
helped lead the campaign against stellos confirmation 
among the accusations against stello is that he altered agency 
rules at the request of nuclear utilities to the detriment of 
safety and that he authorized cash payments to an informer as part 
of a personal vendetta within the nrc 
in two confirmation hearing appearances before the senate armed 
services committee last fall stello strongly denied that he acted 
improperly he asserted that nuclear safety was his primary concern 
and that he was well suited for the job 
the withdrawal of the stello nomination ends an extraordinary 
chapter in the administrations effort to revitalize the crippled 
nuclear weapons complex by putting an experienced nuclear power 
expert in charge for the first time 
key elements of the weapons complex which include 17 major 
production plants and laboratories in 12 states are shut down 
because of safety and management problems 
tom olson an energy department spokesman said stello would 
remain at the department in a civil service job that does not 
require senate confirmation his responsibilities will include 
overseeing efforts to restart idled reactors at the savannah river 
nuclear weapons plant in south carolina olson said 
energy secretary james d watkins said during the senate 
hearings that stello was the only qualified person willing to take 
the job 
olson said tuesday evening that watkins had no comment on 
stellos withdrawal 
the armed services committee was set to recommend stellos 
confirmation in january but balked upon learning that he was the 
focus of an investigation by david williams the nrc inspector 
general 
williams is investigating allegations that stello and other nrc 
officials pursued a vendetta against roger fortuna who was in 
charge of investigating wrongdoing at nuclear plants the 
allegation was that stello believed fortuna was too hard on the 
industry 
the results of williams investigation have not been made 
public but in his letter to bush stello noted that the armed 
services committee planned to hold up further consideration of his 
nomination until it reviewed them 
