<TEXT>
the exxon corp says it isnt happy with the 
way the federal government is trying to assess the longterm 
damages from last years alaska oil spill and doesnt plan to 
contribute any more money for the effort 
officials of an interagency trustee council told a 
congressional hearing tuesday that efforts to determine the 
evironmental damages caused by the massive spill from the tanker 
exxon valdez cost 354 million in the first year more than twice 
the amount provided by exxon 
damage assessment studies to be continued this year could cost 
an additional 30 million according to an internal trustee council 
document made public by a house interior and insular affairs 
subcommittee 
shortly after the march 24 1989 spill in alaskas prince 
william sound exxon agreed to provide 15 million an an initial 
payment for the government damage assessment program interior 
secretary manuel lujan at the time characterized the payment as 
only a first installment from the oil company 
but members of the trustee council told the subcommittee on 
water power and offshore energy resources tuesday that exxon has 
stonewalled requests for additional money 
the trustees have requested that exxon fund the remaining 20 
million of 1989 costs but so far exxon has declined to respond 
to that request said alan raul general counsel of the 
agriculture department and a member of the trustee council 
the minutes of a march meeting of the trustee council released 
by the subcommittee quoted justice department officals as advising 
the participants they should not expect further money from 
exxon 
the cost of damage assessment will be borne by the federal 
government although some of the money likely will be recovered as 
part of the damages sought from exxon in a civil suit that is yet 
to be filed against the oil company 
cm harrison executive vice president of exxon co usa 
acknowledged that exxon plans no further payments for damage 
assessments 
the process has not worked as exxon anticipated harrison 
said in a statement to the subcommittee he complained exxon was 
not given access to data collected as part of the damage assessment 
process and said there was too much emphasis on litigation 
exxon so far has spent more than 1 billion in cleanup costs 
from the spill which contaminated miles of scenic alaska 
coastline the justice department also is pursuing criminal charges 
against exxon that could lead to fines and penalties of more than 
600 million upon conviction 
meanwhile several environment groups complained the damage 
assessment process is inadequate and money shortages are causing 
the trustees to curtail some studies essential to determining 
overall harm to wildlife and natural resources 
it was previously reported that the trustees decided in their 
march meeting not to proceed with 24 of the 63 damage assessment 
studies 
the lawyers and not the scientists have driven the assessment 
process complained erik olson of the national wildlife 
federation he maintained some of the studies were halted because 
they were too expensive and likely would not produce large payoffs 
in damage recovery as a result of the eventual civil suit agaist 
exxon 
apparently decisions on which studies to continue are based 
at least in part on financial considerations said robert adler 
a lawyer for the natural resources defense council 
members of the trustee council are officials of the agriculture 
department interior department and the commerce departments 
national oceanic and atmospheric administration 
