<TEXT>
once the euphoria fades from the homecoming of 
longterm hostages such as robert polhill they risk another 
prison built of depression anger anxiety and a host of other 
mental problems 
they may also face families that learned to live without them 
and a society that forces them to play heroes while blaming them 
for their captivity 
still such problems can be avoided or eased by proper mental 
health care and the basic resilience many hostages show experts 
say 
the remarkable thing isnt that they have problems when they 
return to the environment but that people do successfully return 
that they do reconstruct their lives said dr harry holloway 
chairman of psychiatry at the uniformed services university of the 
health sciences in bethesda md 
in fact david jacobsen who spent nearly 17 months as a captive 
in lebanon before gaining freedom in 1986 says the experience can 
make a person more tolerant and understanding 
you really come to grasp what are the real values of life 
he said in a recent interview you understand what it is as an 
innocent person to make it through another day of hell 
polhill who rejoined his family this week after more than three 
years in captivity in lebanon is at the us air force hospital in 
wiesbaden west germany 
col dr kenneth koskinen medical director of the hospital 
said the exhostage is intellectually very sharp has a great 
sense of humor and considering his ordeal has a reasonably 
positive mental status 
that is encouraging but university of maryland psychiatrist dr 
david mcduff cautioned tuesday that recovery from being a hostage 
is a longterm process that can take many years 
lingering problems can include anger and depression that began 
during captivity said former state department chief psychologist 
samuel karson who oversaw evaluations at the wiesbaden hospital of 
americans who had been hostages in iran 
anger arises as a captive starts thinking why are they doing 
this to me karson said the anger toward captors is compounded 
because a hostage is helpless to act on it he said 
you cant understand their language they have full control 
over you and youre turned into a helpless child all over again 
a hostage can also be angry at the us government for not 
getting him out sooner he said 
depression can begin from the separation from family and the 
insecurity about ones future he said and it does not simply 
disappear upon release he said 
im afraid peoples internal systems dont work like a radio 
or tv set where you just flick the switch now its off he 
said 
immediately after release an exhostage may also dwell 
harmfully on his actions during captivity said mcduff who has 
participated in army teams that recovered hostages and hijacking 
victims 
hostages can become extremely selfcritical as they review 
their actions feelings and thoughts mcduff said they might blame 
themselves for not stopping beatings other hostages received or 
for thoughts about harming their captors he said 
former captives often fail to see that the rules in the middle 
of a period of captivity really have more to do with survival than 
with anything else its not like the normal world 
a released hostage may also risk posttraumatic stress disorder 
which can include excessive dwelling on the hostage experience a 
withdrawing from contacts and activities that might trigger 
recollections and anxiety 
still other difficulties can spring from adjusting to the 
private and public worlds to which a longterm hostage returns his 
children have grown years older shaped by a culture that differs 
markedly from the life he endured for years holloway noted and he 
must fit into a family that has built a life without him holloway 
said 
the hostage also faces the expectations and attitudes of 
society hostages are pressured into the roles of heroes when 
theyre not feeling very heroic holloway said 
paradoxically society may also blame them for being taken 
hostage mcduff said in order to feel comfortable in this 
world he said we have to believe and think that things like 
this dont happen unless somebody does something that makes it 
happen 
what can be done to help newly freed hostages cope with their 
return 
a key step experts say is to give them immediately a week or 
so out of the public eye much like the decompression period 
deepsea divers take to adjust to a normal atmosphere 
during this time hostages can become acquainted with their 
families and the changes they missed they can come to terms with 
their thoughts and actions in captivity they can vent and deal 
with anger 
let them make the choices karson said thats how they 
realize that they really are free again 
</TEXT>
