<DOCNO> AP900425-0046 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in the face of declining readership some 
newspapers are succeeding by remaining close to their subscribers 
and by building loyal reporting staffs with authoritative knowledge 
of the communities they cover 
in a report submitted tuesday at the american newspaper 
publishers association a research group dubbed the ateam told 
what made three newspapers more successful than most 
group members said they found different formulas at the free 
lancestar of fredericksburg va the cedar rapids iowa gazette 
and the pressenterprise of riverside calif 
but one trait was universal they knew their markets cold and 
were always updating their understanding said michelle foster 
marketing director of the newspress of fort myers fla and a 
member of the research group 
seymour topping director of editorial development for the new 
york times regional newspaper group said a team approach to 
running the newspapers helped he added that each gave its readers 
a complete paper with local national and international news 
harold f woldt jr vice presidentcirculation of newsday of 
long island ny pointed to a loyal staff as a key to success at 
all three papers he stressed that only if core personnel are 
retained can they know the communities they serve 
he said the three papers had unusual stability among their 
staff accomplished through publisher involvement better pay and a 
sense of institutional commitment to the newspaper 
the presentation was chaired by william j keating chairman and 
publisher of the cincinnati enquirer who declared the report gave 
him renewed faith that we the newspaper people of america can 
meet the challenge 
in other events tuesday at the associations 104th annual 
convention the nations newspaper publishers discussed declining 
readership telecommunications developments affecting papers and 
recycling of newsprint 
to build greater reader interest an advertising consultant 
advised newspapers to focus on local news suggesting international 
issues dont sell advertising 
the comments came during a panel discussion titled ozzie and 
harriet are gone who do you think youre writing for the 
discussion was moderated by jeff greenfield of abc news 
virginia dodge fielder vice president of research for 
knightridder inc expressed industry frustration over vanishing 
readers 
i wish they expressed more dissatisfaction because if they did 
wed know how to tackle it she said what the public is saying 
is not i hate you but i dont need you 
the session opened with video interviews in which subjects were 
asked if they read a newspaper 
i dont have time was a common response several said tv 
news was easier one man said that since big business had taken 
over his local paper he felt less connected to it the comment 
echoed a message emphasized by laurel cutler vice chairman of 
fcbleber katz partners and vice president of consumer affairs for 
the chrysler corp 
the only specialized thing about a newspaper is its 
locality she told the audience localness is what you have to 
sell 
but frank a daniels jr president and publisher of the news amp 
observer of raleigh nc interjected that a newspaper 
traditionally has been a smorgasbord 
ms cutler warned against newspapers trying to be all things 
to all people 
greenfield suggested that the puzzle of declining readership may 
not be complex is it possible that the reason people read 
newspapers so devotedly in 1940 is there was nothing else to inform 
them he asked 
publishers and editors on the panel disagreed 
one thing you may be overlooking is how adaptable newspapers 
are said c shelby coffey iii editor and executive vice 
president of the los angeles times 
he noted the times has numerous regional bureaus to keep the 
paper local but has inaugurated a world report section on 
global developments research at the times shows that 
international news is of great interest to readers he said 
coffey and gerald garcia editor and publisher of the knoxville 
tenn journal also urged development of a multiethnic reporting 
force 
publishers were also told they must move to recycle newsprint to 
stave off government interference 
frank a bennack jr president and chief executive officer of 
the hearst corp in new york and chairman of the anpa newsprint 
resource task force painted a grim picture of vanishing landfills 
he said publishers have resolved to double the amount of 
recycled newsprint used in the coming year reaching a total of 46 
million tons 
we believe efforts to control newsprint can mean efforts to 
control the press he said the prospect of dealing with a 
regulated newsprint industry calls up an array of terrifying 
unknowns 
he said 35 percent of newspapers are recycled and publishers 
aim to bring that up to 50 percent 
bennack said that in 1979 the nation had 18000 landfills 
available today only 6500 remain he said and by 1995 that 
figure will diminish to 4200 
bennack stressed that newsprint makes up only 8 percent of solid 
waste in landfills 
in a separate development publishers were told they may be 
close to winning a sixyear dispute with the bell 
telecommunications companies 
robert m johnson publisher president and chief executive 
officer of newsday inc of long island ny reported that 
congress is likely to pass a bill soon setting a telecommunications 
public policy 
citing antitrust laws us district judge harold greene held 
that those who control telecommunication lines should not also 
control the information that goes over those lines johnson said 
he recounted that bell companies lobbied for exceptions to the 
1984 court ruling on the breakup of atampt 
johnson said the bell companies have set aside a 25 million 
war chest to fight to publish information on electronic 
circuits he said bell seeks to launch an electronic yellow 
pages in competition with newspaper ads 
an anpa task force has worked with congress johnson said 
the result of those long negotiations was a new draft bill 
he said it is from our point of view the best piece of 
legislation weve seen 
the bill has not yet been passed an appeal of the original 
federal order has sent that back to greene for reconsideration 
