<TEXT>
here are some facts and figures on 
nicaragua where violeta barrios de chamorro is to be inaugurated 
as president today 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the land nicaragua is the largest country in central america 
about the size of iowa with 57000 square miles 
a coastal plain rolls from the pacific coast to the central 
mountains providing the country with rich farmland farms and 
ranches dot the mountains the eastern half of the country is 
sparsely populated crisscrossed by rivers and dominated by the 
steamy jungles of the miskito coast along the caribbean 
no road connects the two coasts 
a string of more than 50 volcanos runs northwest to southeast 
near the pacific coast one of nicaraguas two large lakes contains 
the worlds only freshwater sharks 
a dec 23 1972 earthquake and fires destroyed the center of 
managua much of the capital has not been rebuilt and remains a 
wasteland of weedy lots and skeletons of buildings 
nicaragua is bordered by honduras on the north costa rica on 
the south 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the people nicaragua has 35 million people about 90 percent 
living in the western half of the country and about half under age 
16 
managua the most populous city has 850000 residents 
spanish is the official language english and native indian 
languages mostly miskito are spoken by ethnic minorities along 
the caribbean coast 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the economy exports of coffee cotton sesame and beef provide 
most of nicaraguas income from 700 million in 1978 the year 
before the sandinistas came to power exports dropped to 200 
million in 1989 at the height of the us trade embargo 
inflation for 1989 was 1700 percent according to the 
government a figure that many experts think is low in 1988 
prices rose 33600 percent the currency the cordoba has been 
steadily devalued in line with inflation 
president bush lifted the 1985 us embargo on march 13 and 
asked congress for 300 million in aid including 45 million to 
demobilize and relocate the contras 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
history spain conquered nicaraguas various indian tribes in 
1552 the country won independence from spain in 1821 
relations with the united states have long been traumatic 
in the 1850s american adventurer william walker invaded the 
country several times once declaring himself president 
early in the 1900s us marines occupied the country leaving 
for the last time in 1933 augusto cesar sandino became a national 
hero fighting the americans he was killed in 1934 and the united 
states installed gen anastasio somoza founder of a 42year somoza 
family dynasty 
the last somoza anastasio somoza debayle was overthrown july 
19 1979 in a revolution led by the sandinista national liberation 
front named after sandino 
discontent after nine years of war and increasing economic 
deterioration helped mrs chamorro oust sandinista president daniel 
ortega in a feb 25 vote mrs chamorro is the widow of pedro 
joaquin chamorro a somoza opponent whose assassination in january 
1978 consolidated support for the sandinista revolt 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

