its only a single faucet by the side 
of a dirt road but its more than the residents of the sunny sky 
subdivision have ever had in their poor neighborhood 
drinking water flowed for the first time tuesday to more than 40 
residents of the colonia the border region is dotted with 
similar communities of plywood homes and trailers without water or 
sewage connections 
after lawyers used the state consumer protection act to go after 
the developer residents gathered tuesday at the spigot to 
celebrate they said they hope one day to have water lines all the 
way to their houses 
this is very good because the children have to be clean to go 
to school said eulalio hernandez a father of six 
socorro de la rosa who has three children smiled as she 
watched the water flow into a plastic bucket lets bathe ms 
de la rosa said as she carried a neighbors laughing 5yearold and 
washed his face in the water 
she said she had worried about people washing with irrigation 
water from the polluted rio grande that flows from pipes near the 
homes at sunny sky 
previously residents of sunny sky had to travel about a mile to 
gather barrels and buckets of water at another colonia that has 
potable water they will continue to use outhouses in their back 
yards 
the water hookup is the work of al alvarez an assistant state 
attorney general 
alvarez used the state deceptive trade practices consumer 
protection act to get a court order that directed residents 
mortgage payments to his office instead of to the developer the 
money went toward water service 
the developer was telling people there would be water hookup 
and soon there would be sewer service alvarez said he never 
intended to do that he knew from the very beginning that this 
would be an illegal subdivision 
