an emergency aid package for panama and 
nicaragua will pass the senate easily and president bush will be 
able to sign it soon a democratic senator predicted today 
the appropriations committee gave the presidents drive for 
emergency aid to the two countries a boost late tuesday by 
approving a 720 million economic recovery package 
on a 1514 vote the committee spurned a request by its 
chairman sen robert c byrd to cut the aid to panama and use the 
extra money for a program to help us businesses compete in the 
new markets of eastern europe 
byrd dwva had teamed with sen patrick leahy dvt in 
seeking to provide just 300 million to panama this year and a like 
amount to nicaragua bush had asked for 500 million for panama 
the committee rejected byrds proposal and adopted instead an 
amendment by sen robert kasten rwis boosting the panama figure 
to 420 million the same amount endorsed by the house on april 3 
i predict that the aid package will pass the senate easily 
and the president will be able to sign it into law in a short 
time leahy said today on nbcs today program 
the package swelled to about 34 billion by the addition of 
money for a long list of domestic programs was expected to come up 
for debate in the full senate today 
leahy said the aid to nicaragua probably would be the first 
installment in a lengthy program to rebuild that nations economy 
we are going to have to be committed to nicaragua for as many 
years as we were committed to destroying it with the contra policy 
i suspect that eventually the united states is going to end up 
spending billions of dollars in this tiny country he said 
final passage was being delayed until thursday because some 
senators were traveling to nicaragua for the inauguration of the 
new usbacked president violeta chamorro 
the bill is nearly 1 billion more expensive than the version 
the house approved like the house measure most of the new 
spending would be financed through cuts in this years pentagon 
budget 
among senate addons to the bill were 110 million for the 
census bureau to help complete the lagging 1990 population count 
1658 million to increase head start rolls by an additional 60000 
disadvantaged children 8 million to fight grasshoppers in the 
upper midwest 705 million for the food stamp program and 
additional money for veterans pensions and medical care 
another provision would set aside 10 million to build and staff 
a new us embassy in lithuania should the administration decide 
to formally recognize the independence of the baltic state 
the measure also adds a provision that would allow the district 
of columbia to use local funds to pay for abortions language that 
brought two presidential vetoes last year 
the appropriations committee claimed nearly 28 billion in 
savings from the military budget the first application of a 
peace dividend from lessened eastwest tensions the savings 
included the effects of a freeze on hiring civilian personnel and 
cuts in military construction weapons procurement and research 
but the committee restored 238 million for construction of a 
new army explosives plant in louisiana the home state of 
democratic sen j bennett johnston a panel member the money had 
been deleted in the house version of the bill 
