artillery battles raged today between 
gen michel aouns troops and samir geageas militia setting pine 
forests ablaze as the 3monthold struggle for control of lebanons 
christian enclave flared anew 
police said at least two people were killed and 12 wounded that 
raised the known casualty toll since the fighting began jan 30 to 
at least 896 killed and 2411 wounded most of them civilians 
the fighting in east beirut and other sectors of the 
310squaremile christian enclave north of the capital broke out 
shortly before daybreak 
the exchanges subsided into intermittent mortar and machine gun 
clashes around 830 am but fierce howitzer duels broke out again 
at midday 
the escalation came one day after geagea imposed a sea blockade 
on aouns makeshift port at dbaye north of beirut to prevent the 
general from shipping in ammunition for his artillery and heavy 
weapons 
dbaye is aouns only outlet to the mediterreanean all the other 
ports in the christian enclave are held by geageas rightwing 
militia 
aouns headquarters said the blockade by geageas gunboats was 
an act of piracy 
pillars of flames shot up from the wooded smokeshrouded 
mountain slopes of the christian hinterland as radio stations 
broadcast an appeal from maronite catholic patriarch nasrallah 
sfeir for a ceasefire 
the police spokesman who cannot be named under standing 
regulations said several shells hit residential districts of 
moslem west beirut which has not been involved in the christian 
fighting but no casualties were reported there 
the moslemrun voice of the nation radio station blamed the 
escalation on aoun and noted that the fighting flared after reports 
that president elias hrawis government will not pay civil servants 
in areas controlled by the maverick general 
beiruts independent annahar daily said that hrawis 
syrianbacked government will meet next week to adopt a decision to 
pay only government employees who declare their loyalty to the 
legal authority 
aoun does not recognize hrawi as head of state he has also 
rejected an arab leaguebrokered peace plan to end lebanons 
15yearold civil war between christians and moslems 
hrawi is supposed to implement the accord endorsed by lebanons 
parliament in taif saudi arabia in october 
aoun geagea and hrawi are maronite catholics the largest 
christian sect which has dominated political life in lebanon since 
independence from france in 1943 
civil servants in the christian enclave have not received their 
monthly wages since the beginning of the year 
the battles between aoun and geagea broke out one day before 
payday in january and hrawis government has not transferred funds 
from the central bank in west beirut to cover salaries for civil 
servants in the enclave 
geagea has recognized hrawi and called on his government to take 
over public utilities in areas controlled by his militia which 
include the christian hinterland in the kesrouan and byblos 
provinces as well as two isolated pockets in east beirut 
aoun controls the southeast of the capitals christian sector 
the metn mountains northeast of the city and a 3mile stretch of 
coast on the northern edge of beirut 
