<TEXT>
britains house of commons has cut the time limit 
on legal abortions from 28 weeks one of the most liberal in the 
western world to 24 
prolife groups had demanded the time limit be cut to 18 weeks 
but the commons in a series of votes tuesday rejected calls to 
set the limit at 18 weeks 20 weeks 22 weeks or 26 weeks or to 
retain the 28week limit 
the lawmakers chose a 24week limit by 409 votes to 152 in a 
free vote meaning legislators could vote according to conscience 
rather than party lines 
the new limit will be written into the human fertilization and 
embryology bill which is expected to become law this year 
the new limit applies in most routine cases but in other votes 
the commons allowed exemptions 
abortions now will not be subject to any time limit if an 
abortion is needed to prevent grave permanent injury to the 
physical or mental health of the pregnant woman or if substantial 
risk exists of the fetus developing into a baby with a serious 
handicap 
on monday the house of commons voted to write into the same 
bill a provision permitting continued research into human embryos 
up to 14 days after conception 
the 28week limit one of the most liberal provisions in the 
western world has been in force since britain first legalized 
abortion in 1967 
virginia bottomley a minister of state at the department of 
health backed the abortion law change she told the commons 
some fetuses of less than 28 weeks gestation which would at one 
time have stood little chance of surviving after birth now have a 
greater chance of survival 
jo richardson the spokeswoman on womens affairs for the 
socialist opposition labor party said the overwhelming majority of 
people in britain particularly women wanted to leave the limit at 
28 weeks 
legislator ann widdecombe a member of the governing 
conservative party and a leading prolife campaigner cited the 
case of a 21weekold aborted fetus that lived for three hours in a 
kidney dish gasping for life at carlisle general hospital in 
northwest england before dying 
to any member of parliament thinking of voting for a limit 
above the 21 weeks it would not have saved the carlisle baby 
she said 
conservative legislator sir bernard braine who supported an 
18week limit said that since the legalization of abortion in 
1967 up to 3 million children had been lost the overwhelming 
majority would have been born fit and healthy he said 
</TEXT>
