<TEXT>
hundreds of tibetan monks have walked out of 
their monasteries to protest a move by chinese authorities to expel 
some of their proindependence colleagues a tibet monitoring 
organization reported today 
the londonbased tibet information network said about 200 monks 
at the sera monastery and a large number at the drepung 
monastery in the tibetan capital of lhasa staged the walkout last 
week after chinese authorities expelled dozens of monks for 
advocating tibetan independence 
efforts to reach the monasteries and offices in lhasa to confirm 
the report were unsuccessful chinese telephone operators often do 
not connect calls to the remote himalayan region 
lhasa remains under martial law imposed in march 1989 after 
nationalist riots and no journalists have been allowed in recently 
the tibet information network said a witness in lhasa whom it 
did not identify reported that the monks at the sera monastery 
posted a notice on their gate on april 19 announcing the walkout 
the notice said chinese authorities had expelled three monks 
from sera on april 16 and otherwise interfered in monastery 
operations it declared that tibet was an independent country and 
the chinese should leave 
an unspecified number of monks at the nearby drepung monastery 
walked out on april 17 to protest the expulsion of 37 of their 
colleagues the day before the network said it quoted an 
unidentified witness as saying that only older monks too weak to 
travel stayed behind 
the protesting monks are believed to have returned to their home 
villages 
chinese authorities also expelled 18 monks from the ganden 
monastery outside lhasa and seven from the jokhang temple lhasas 
oldest and holiest religious site the network said it said it 
received unconfirmed reports that more than 150 nuns were expelled 
at about the same time from four nunneries around lhasa 
buddhist nuns and monks have led repeated independence 
demonstrations in recent years and remain loyal to their top 
religious leader the exiled dalai lama from india where he fled 
in 1959 after a failed tibetan uprising the dalai lama has 
criticized chinas heavyhanded rule in tibet and appealed for 
autonomy or independence 
china insists that its sovereignty over tibet dates back to the 
13th century and refuses to accept any weakening of its control 
however there were long periods when tibet had virtually no 
contact with china and was ruled by a theocracy headed by the dalai 
lama 
in the 1950s and 1960s the communists destroyed most of tibets 
monasteries and banned religious worship only in the past decade 
have some temples and monasteries been reopened 
four times since late 1987 tibetan independence protests have 
resulted in bloody clashes with security forces since the last 
protests culminated in riots march 58 1989 chinese authorities 
have stationed security forces in all the monasteries and begun 
intensive political education of monks and nuns 
</TEXT>
