<TEXT>
a federal appeals court says two men who 
fled to this country may not be deported and are eligible for 
asylum because el salvadors threat to imprison men who refuse 
military service on moral grounds is religious persecution 
the 21 ruling tuesday by the 9th us circuit court of appeals 
overruled the immigration and naturalization service which had 
rejected the asylum applications 
the two salvadorans are jehovahs witnesses a church whose 
members refuse to bear arms 
the ins said el salvadors refusal to exempt men with moral 
objections to war from military service was not religious 
persecution because it applied to everyone equally 
but the appeals court cited the united nations refugee agencys 
handbook which interprets international refugee treaties as 
allowing asylum claims by conscientious objectors from countries 
that do not recognize that status 
a conscientious objector is one whose actions are governed by 
conscience and persecution arises whenever that conscience is 
overcome by force or punishment meted out for the refusal to betray 
it said the opinion by judge eugene wright 
the ins could appeal the ruling to the supreme court lawyers 
for the agency did not return telephone calls to comment 
lawyers supporting the salvadorans and representatives of 
amnesty international and the united nations high commissioner for 
refugees said it was the first appellate decision in the nation to 
grant refugee status to aliens who fled their home country because 
it did not recognize conscientious objections to war 
the case before the court involved oscar canassegovia and his 
older brother jose who fled el salvador at ages 16 and 17 in 1985 
because their religions objections to military service would not 
be recognized they were arrested two days after entering the 
united states 
the brothers fled their homeland after seeing friends taken by 
soldiers from street corners and forcibly conscripted into the 
military said their lawyer karen musalo 
at their immigration hearing they also offered evidence from a 
human rights expert clergy and others in el salvador about torture 
and murder of those who refuse to join the armed forces 
ms musalo said the brothers now live in the san francisco area 
the 9th circuit ruling said the threat of imprisonment or other 
punishment for refusing military service out of genuine 
political religious or moral convictions or other genuine reasons 
of conscience was an act of religious persecution under us 
and international law 
the court also called the threat political persecution saying 
voluminous and convincing evidence showed that salvadorans who 
refused the draft were often viewed as enemies of the government 
and faced a risk of torture or death 
the court quoted an immigration judge as saying el salvador was 
one of 40 nations that refuse to grant conscientious objector 
status 
judge procter hug joined the opinion judge edward leavy agreed 
on the finding of political persecution but dissented on the 
religious issue saying an intent to persecute must be shown 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

