<TEXT>
medical facilities for victims of the 1984 
bhopal gas disaster are running out of money and may have to shut 
down a senior state official warned wednesday 
compounding problems faced by survivors of the union carbide gas 
leak banks here say they are not equipped to handle monthly relief 
payments ordered by prime minister vp singh 
treatment and compensation for victims of the worlds worst 
industrial disaster most of whom are poor shantytown dwellers 
have been bogged down in a tangle of bureaucracy lawsuits and 
politics for more than five years 
we will be impelled to close down the hospitals and other 
health care facilities if financial assistance does not come 
through soon said sr sathyam gas relief commissioner in 
madhya pradesh state 
he said the state government had sent an sos to the central 
government in new delhi 
the madhya pradesh government has spent 21 million in state 
funds since the dec 3 1984 gas leak sathyam said in an interview 
there is now no money to pay salaries to the hospital staff 
deliver free milk to children train the gas victims in various 
crafts and trades and extend loans to them he added 
meanwhile banks in bhopal the state capital said the central 
governments order for monthly relief payments would stretch their 
staffs too thin they suggested quarterly relief payments since 
