<DOCNO> AP900425-0107 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a form of a natural body chemical appears to 
significantly reduce the complications of kidney transplants 
cutting in half the risk that the new organ will be rejected 
according to a study 
doctors found that misoprostol a synthetic version of the 
substance prostaglandin reduced the risk of organ rejection from 
51 percent to 26 percent 
in the comparison study doctors tested misoprostol in 
combination with cyclosporine a medicine that has been widely used 
since the early 1980s to prevent organ rejection 
prostaglandins are made by tissue throughout the body and serve 
a variety of purposes cyclosporine interferes with the ability of 
the kidneys to make the substance 
the study was directed by dr mark moran of gd searle and co 
the pharmaceutical firm that makes misoprostol the medicine is 
currently approved to prevent gastric ulcers that can occur when 
people are treated for inflammation 
the research published in thursdays new england journal of 
medicine compared 39 transplant patients who took cyclosporine and 
other standard medicines with 38 patients who also received 
misoprostol 
when rejection occurs patients must receive extra doses of 
medicines that suppress their bodys diseasefighting immune 
systems while this frequently allows them to keep their new 
organs it leaves them susceptible to infections 
it seems likely that prostaglandin will have several uses 
because of its ability to reduce rejection and improve kidney 
function in patients with all sorts of transplants said moran 
this also suggests that we may be able to reduce doses of other 
more toxic immunosuppressants 
an editorial by dr charles b carpenter of brigham and womens 
hospital in boston said the work appears to confirm animal studies 
he said it should promote more intensive investigation of 
prostaglandin therapy 
in a separate report in the journal dr jeanpaul soulillou and 
others from the national institute of health and medical research 
in nantes france tested a different approach to blocking 
rejection 
they gave patients antibodies that attacked one variety of 
freshly activated white blood cells known as t leukocytes they 
said it worked as well as another treatment using antibodies that 
were not specifically targeted against these cells but it produced 
fewer unwanted side effects 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

