<DOCNO> AP900425-0117 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a new form of a common high blood pressure 
medicine appears to slow the lifethreatening lung damage of cystic 
fibrosis and could dramatically improve the lives of people with 
the frequent inherited disorder 
the conclusions were from a preliminary study of the medicine 
amiloride 
the medicine when inhaled in a spray form seemed to help clear 
thick secretions that clog cystic fibrosis patients lungs it 
reduced the loss of lung capacity by 60 percent when compared to a 
dummy treatment 
cystic fibrosis strikes about one in 2500 babies born in the 
united states only about half of the victims live to their 
mid20s and almost all of the deaths are from lung disease 
because of an inherited abnormality in people with cystic 
fibrosis the cells that line the air tubes in their lungs absorb 
too much salt and water this produces a thick mucous that blocks 
the lungs and makes victims prone to infections and breathing 
problems 
amiloride a diuretic appears to work by reducing the lung 
cells absorption of salt and water 
in the initial study doctors tried the treatment on adults 
whose lungs were already seriously damaged by years of infection 
no one has tried it yet on youngsters whose lungs are still 
relatively healthy but researchers hope it will significantly 
change the course of their illness 
our fantasy is that it could be much more useful if given 
early in life over the long haul said dr michael r knowles a 
developer of the treatment at the university of north carolina 
he cautioned however that the diuretic which is ordinarily 
used to prevent water retention could be harmful to childrens 
kidneys or have other unwanted side effects 
dr robert beall research director of the cystic fibrosis 
foundation said that a study is planned that will test the 
medicine on youngsters under age 12 
it could increase life exponentially beall said we feel 
that if we can change the environment of the lung so that we dont 
give bacteria a good place to live we might add decades to these 
kids lives 
a report on knowles initial study conducted on 14 adults was 
published in thursdays new england journal of medicine 
for two consecutive sixmonth periods they used aerosol 
amiloride or a placebo while their conditions did not improve the 
rate of lung damage appeared to be slowed while taking amiloride 
cystic fibrosis is now treated primarily by giving antibiotics 
and pounding on victims chests to loosen the mucous in their 
lungs the new approach exploits several years of research into the 
underlying abnormality in cystic fibrosis 
what is particularly exciting is that we for the first time 
have used a therapy that tries to treat the primary defect which 
is the abnormal movement of ions across the membranes said 
beall we are going to the source of the problem 
amiloride has been available in the united states in pill form 
for five years to treat high blood pressure congestive heart 
failure and fluid retention associated with kidney disease 
however the pills are ineffective against cystic fibrosis 
knowles and two other researchers hold the patent on the aerosol 
technique the pharmaceutical firm glaxo has bought the rights to 
produce the inhaled form of the drug 
more testing will be necessary before permission is sought from 
the us food and drug administration to make the treatment 
routinely available until then cystic fibrosis patients will be 
able to obtain the therapy only by enrolling in experimental trials 
of the medication 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

