<DOCNO> AP900425-0121 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the sheer size of dinosaurs may have helped them 
live in a variety of climates without getting too hot or cold a 
study of huge turtles suggests 
researchers found evidence that large coldblooded animals can 
keep constant high body temperatures by large body size low 
metabolic rate and the use of some peripheral tissues as insulation 
the study focused on leatherback turtles which are among the 
largest living reptiles they can weigh more than 1500 pounds 
the turtles range from the tropics to near the arctic circle 
they can warm up on land and keep elevated body temperatures in 
cold seawater researchers said 
scientists measured metabolic rates of six adult females and 
mathematically analyzed the turtles ability to maintain a 
relatively high internal temperature 
leatherbacks may restrict the flow of blood to the skin to keep 
warm and increase it to avoid overheating researchers said 
support for that idea comes in the observation that the turtles 
soft skin appears to be flushed with blood while the animal nests 
the researchers said 
the scientists suggested that their proposed 
temperatureregulating system for large animals be called 
gigantothermy 
such a system may have allowed dinosaurs to live in a wide 
variety of habitats including polar regions the researchers said 
the work is reported in thursdays issue of the british journal 
nature by scientists from drexel university in philadelphia and 
purdue university in fort wayne ind 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

