<TEXT>
a new radar system that will allow military 
observers to look over the earths horizon and get an earlier 
warning of enemy aircraft or drugsmuggling planes has been turned 
over to the air force 
by being able to detect enemy aircraft farther away the air 
force gets as long as 3 hours to respond to a threat of an attack 
compared with perhaps only a few minutes with conventional radar 
systems officials said 
the 680 million backscatter system turned over to the military 
tuesday gives the air force eyes over a semicircular 45 
millionsquaremile swath across the atlantic from greenland to 
cuba the air force said 
the operations center is based in the outskirts of this central 
maine city and the antennas are in moscow moscow maine that is 
the maine system is the first of four that will eventually form 
an early warning shield around most of north americas perimeter 
its range of up to 1800 miles is nearly 10 times greater than than 
of conventional radar 
while the overthehorizon system was designed primarily to give 
the air force more time to spot enemy bombers it will also be 
useful in detecting small planes carrying illegal narcotics said 
col john o lenz the systems program director 
enemy cruise missiles however would be a very difficult 
target perhaps the most difficult target for this type of 
radar lenz said after the air force took possession of the 
bangor operations center from general electric co 
the air force plans to hire private contractors to run the 
operations center by mid1992 although the most sensitive 
decisionmaking roles such as whether to call for a military 
response to an errant plane will remain in military hands us 
and canadian air force personnel are currently staffing the center 
a bank of 16 computer systems collects the required flight plans 
from all planes that enter the backscatter systems range telling 
technicians whether aircraft represented by blips on their computer 
screens belong in that airspace 
if they dont have a flight plan it enables the operator to 
say id better take another look at this said capt alan m 
chilton of the canadian air force 
the system gains its extraordinary reach by bouncing radar 
signals off the earths ionosphere enabling the radar to hopscotch 
over the planets curve that layer of the atmosphere is also 
responsible for bouncing shortwave radio signals around the world 
the radar signal begins its journey from three 3600footlong 
antenna arrays in the western maine town of moscow return signals 
bouncing back from aircraft are picked up 100 miles away by three 
receivers each nearly a mile long in the town of columbia falls 
a similar overthehorizon system with components in california 
idaho and oregon is 90 percent complete and is expected to come on 
line in about a year its range will be a half donutshaped area 
across the pacific from alaska to south of baja mexico 
the planned central system with components in north dakota 
south dakota and minnesota will focus on the southern part of the 
continent an alaskan system will point toward the western part of 
the soviet union 
the system is not effective directly north of the continent 
because of electrical disturbances in the atmosphere that produce 
the northern lights conventional radar guards against intruders 
from the north 
</TEXT>
