census workers turn to doortodoor counting 
thursday with the bureau facing escalating costs and criticism of 
its efforts so far this year 
only 63 percent of the nations households have responded by 
mail leaving the census takers the task of driving riding and 
walking to the remainder of homes 
original plans had anticipated a 70 percent response and the 
shortfall could help add 150 million or more to the projected 13 
billion cost of the 1990 census 
the work beginning thursday covers more than 100 metropolitan 
areas across the nation as counters try to track down folks who 
either didnt get a census form or failed to mail theirs back 
individual counting expands to an additional 300 smaller 
communities may 3 census officials report 
in rural areas which were not included in the mail portion of 
the count personal visits by census takers have been going on 
since march 
the national head count began in march with the mailing of more 
than 95 million census forms 
the official counters can be identified by their red white and 
blue identification badges and satchels the bureau reported 
although the housetohouse count is now starting government 
officials continue to encourage americans to mail back forms if 
they have not done so 
counting americans at home will continue at least through june 
officials report longer if needed 
members of congress have been highly critical of the early 
census effort noting that large areas of some big cities have been 
overlooked in the mail count 
in addition a coalition of cities and interest groups has filed 
suit against the bureau contending that minorities are being 
undercounted and seeking to force a statistical adjustment of the 
final census figures 
