solidarity ended its national congress 
wednesday after an allnight session attended by chairman lech 
walesa who said the union now is united to face polands problems 
now we have the mandate we are organized for when life brings 
its problems said a proud walesa from the rostrum as the 
congress ended at 8 am 
the sevenday congress the trade unions second reelected 
walesa as chairman it also approved a new charter and program and 
chose a 96member national commission ending longsimmering 
disputes about the legitimacy of solidaritys leadership structure 
after the chaos caused by martial law in 1981 
the new program calls for solidarity to concentrate mainly on 
trade union issues while not withdrawing totally from its role as a 
broad political movement the union retains the option to create 
its own political party if it sees the need 
the solutions are not perfect but in the present situation 
perfect solutions do not exist walesa said 
the essence of the congress was when a chance lies ahead for 
the country to be united and organized as a practical person i 
am happy about this he said 
the congress gave an overwhelming vote of confidence to walesas 
leadership since the unions first congress in october 1981 he has 
guided the union from its years as an underground organization 
through the long negotiations that led to its regaining legal 
status a year ago 
the same negotiations opened the door to a solidarityled 
government for poland which led the wave of reform in the east 
bloc 
the position of walesa is now really indisputable said one 
warsaw delegate marcin przybylowicz 
still walesa did come under criticism for his authoritarian 
style of leadership during the debates in closing remarks he 
appeared to be trying to make amends 
this congress brought a few surprises it did not go exactly 
along with my concept but i never took the floor even though my 
tongue was jumping out because i did not want to disturb 
democracy he said 
many delegates emerged from the meeting convinced walesa is 
planning a bid for polands presidency using the union as a base 
walesa has been evasive in discussing his presidential plans 
president wojciech jaruzelskis term ends in 1995 the congress 
however passed a resolution calling for new parliamentary and 
presidential elections by the spring of 1991 
he is citizen no 1 in this country and if the alternative is 
jaruzelski of course it is great if he runs said delegate jan 
waszkiewicz of walesa 
but other union members appeared disappointed at the prospect 
myself and others would feel cheated if he ran for the 
chairman of the union with the intention of becoming president 
said alojzy pietrzyk the miners leader for the region of silesia 
walesa and the new national commission were elected to serve a 
threeyear term and the next national solidarity congress is to be 
held in one year 
the congress took place in a calm atmosphere that contrasted 
sharply with its last stormy 18day meeting in 1981 that took 
place under a barrage of hostile criticism from communist 
authorities in warsaw moscow and other east bloc capitals 
in 1981 crowds gathered outside the oliva sports hall to be 
close to the debates there were no similar displays of enthusiasm 
this time with life in gdansk proceeding normally 
prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki and deputy prime minister 
leszek balcerowicz architect of polands stringent economic reform 
program made appearances at the congress 
but relations between solidarity and the government it helped 
create remained uneasy a minority of delegates advocated the union 
make a clean break with the governments painful economic policies 
and concentrate on protecting workers interests 
