a house agriculture subcommittee wednesday 
approved a foreign trade section of the 1990 farm bill that would 
allow food giveaways to needy countries 
the legislation is similar to the senate measure on foreign 
trade approved in committee earlier this month the farm bill will 
set agriculture policy for the next five years 
the major difference between the two bills is the way the food 
aid programs would be managed within the government according to a 
house subcommittee spokeswoman 
both bills would allow the president to give food to countries 
whose governments he wants to encourage such as those in eastern 
europe such assistance now must be in the form of a sale 
the bills also allow the united states to forgive the debts of 
financially strapped countries trying to restructure their 
economies 
both the house and the senate followed bush administration 
recommendations in writing their bills 
ann veneman deputy undersecretary for international affairs and 
commodity programs said the chief difference the administration 
has with either bill is in the language dealing with the export 
enhancement program 
the program offers exporters bonuses for sales of certain 
products to particular countries and is used to reduce the cost of 
us goods in the international marketplace 
the senate bill says the agriculture department must spend at 
least 900 million in fiscal 1991 on the program the house version 
requires that 500 million be spent 
the administration does not want any specific dollar amount 
named 
its a tradepolicy tool veneman said adding that the 
amount spent should be the prerogative of the administration 
