president mikhail s gorbachev traveled to the 
depths of russia on wednesday to ease soviets fears about the 
transition to a market economy but also got an earful of complaints 
about empty store shelves 
after a day of chats with workers in sverdlovsk an industrial 
center 870 miles east of moscow gorbachev admitted its 
apparent that the peoples expectations are at their limit their 
patience is at a limit 
the kremlin chief said he made the trip his first since he was 
elected to the expanded post of executive president last month to 
see how people feel about planned economic reforms 
major social unrest including strikes are feared if the 
government carries out a preliminary plan to free prices establish 
a stock exchange close inefficient industries and move toward 
making the ruble a freely convertible currency 
inflation and unemployment could result from the phasing out of 
price subsidies and the closure of unprofitable factories 
officials have said an economic safety net will be set up to 
help lowincome families cope with the blows 
gorbachev assured the sverdlovsk workers no final decisions had 
been made and wont be until may 10 the changes themselves are six 
to eight months away he added 
someone is throwing out the idea that somebody at the top 
