<TEXT>
courtordered secrecy agreements are helping 
hide information about dangerous products environmental hazards 
medical malpractice and unfair business practices according to 
consumers lawyers and journalists attending a conference wednesday 
but proponents of the agreements argued that the accords are 
private and should be maintained that they are necessary to 
protect manufacturers trade secrets and american competitiveness 
in international markets and that the civil court system is not 
designed to disseminate information obtained in litigation 
information gathered during a lawsuit can be kept secret through 
protective orders confidentiality agreements or judicial sealing 
of files 
such arrangements prohibit lawsuit participants from 
distributing information they obtain limit what can be shared with 
others not involved in the lawsuit or make all records in a case 
unavailable to the public 
in some cases even the names of people or companies involved in 
a suit are kept secret with the court record titled sealed vs 
sealed 
secrecy buries critical facts and the public good is 
ignored and damaged by such practices said russ herman 
president of the association of trial lawyers of america as he 
opened the conference 
in far too many of these cases were not talking about 
irrelevant facts better left in the files of the litigants said 
paul mcmasters deputy editorial director of usa today 
were talking about documents and decisions involving unsafe 
products dangerous drugs toxic wastes all with potentially 
devastating effect on people unaware of the danger added 
mcmasters who heads the freedom of information committee of the 
society of professional journalists cosponsor of wednesdays 
conference 
but james morris iii a virginia attorney argued that the 
practice isnt limited to corporate information 
youre personal papers are also in those files he warned 
if you can summons my medical records from my doctor my diary 
from my psychiatrist or records of design from a company 
privacy goes out the window said morris 
herman argued that such arrangements keep vital health and 
safety information from the press the regulatory agencies and the 
public 
us businesses are at a competitive disadvantage because 
international agreements dont force foreign companies to release 
the same extensive information countered morris 
opponents of the practice said the agreements have become a 
commonly used threat of lengthy legal battle and tactic to 
bribe injured people and their families into settlement 
a compromise is a compromise countered morris if you sue 
for 24 million and take 6 million you werent bribed 
people who bring lawsuits against companies for potentially 
dangerous products concede to the agreements because they cant 
afford to continue litigation and they want to go on with their 
lives said fred barbee barbees wife carol died after an 
artificial heart valve fractured 
he later learned she might have been saved if emergency room 
doctors had treated her for the fractured valve and not the heart 
attack they thought she was having 
morris said the agreements are private litigation between 
private individuals and companies protected by the first 
amendment 
there is nothing in the first amendment that says you are 
entitled to everything in a court file 
how can you call it private unless you can limit it to my 
family asked barbee 
a proposal backed by the bush administration to create a 
uniform federal standard for imposing punitive damages in product 
liability lawsuits and limit to two years most product liability 
claims is pending in a senate subcommittee 
