a change in federal labeling for lean beef has 
gone over well with consumers the agriculture department said 
wednesday 
the labeling took effect in november 1987 after consumers and 
industry petitioned usda for a name change in official federal beef 
grading said jimmy wise of the departments agricultural marketing 
service 
consumers told us they wanted a more positive description of 
leaner meat available in grocery stores and they got it he said 
the change involved scrapping the 60yearold usda good 
label and substituting a usda lean label on supermarket cuts 
many nutritionconscious consumers wanted the name change 
because they felt the good label misled buyers into thinking 
the beef was mediocre when the label was established in the 1920s 
it described the amount of fat or marbling in a cut of beef 
a common consumer view was that less fat was more healthful and 
that the good label wasnt very descriptive 
