<TEXT>
polio probably will be stamped out by the end 
of the year in the western hemisphere according to public health 
experts who say health workers are making surprising progress 
against the crippling disease in latin america 
when the pan american health organization in 1985 set 1990 as a 
goal for eradicating polio in the americas we all said this is 
going to be tough that probably is optimistic da 
henderson dean of the johns hopkins school of public health said 
in an interview wednesday 
then suddenly this program began to move and polio has 
vanished at a pace we could not believe said henderson 
president of the association of schools of public health which met 
in washington this week 
at the moment were having a hard time finding the virus at 
all he said crediting efforts that included health workers 
going doortodoor with the vaccine in urban and other high risk 
areas 
last year 22 cases of infection from the virus were reported in 
central and south america with most occurring in areas along the 
western coast of mexico and the andean countries of peru ecuador 
and colombia henderson said 
before the polio vaccine was introduced in 1954 thousands of 
people in the united states were paralyzed by the disease every 
year the last cases of polio in the united sates were reported in 
the late 1970s 
worldwide there were about 250000 cases of polio last year 
the shortened name for poliomyelitis which is caused by a virus in 
contaminated water or food 
the biggest problem areas are in india bangladesh pakistan and 
subsaharan africa henderson said 
the pan american health organization has set the year 2000 as 
the goal for global eradication of polio 
but ridding the world of polio is proving more difficult than 
the campaign that eradicated smallpox in 1977 henderson said 
the polio vaccine must be kept refrigerated until it is 
administered and this has posed a problem in getting supplies of 
the vaccine into areas of developing nations he said 
also surveillance was easier with smallpox since those infected 
with the virus had a rash polio infection is evident when an 
infected person becomes paralyzed but only one in 100 people 
infected with the polio virus become paralyzed in the others the 
infection is silent and immunizes the carrier from further 
infection for life henderson said 
freeing the western hemisphere from the crippling disease will 
be a big step toward the global goal but it will be more 
difficult to eradicate the disease in the eastern hemisphere he 
said 
