<TEXT>
the bush administration on wednesday asked 
congress to strengthen the food and drug administrations authority 
to act against companies that abuse or defraud the agency 
the legislation was submitted in response to the generic drug 
scandal in which drug manufacturers were found to have 
misrepresented their products and bribed fda officials to win 
approval to market their drugs 
we must have the legal tools to move quickly and decisively 
against anyone who seeks to mislead or subvert the fda said 
health and human services secretary louis sullivan 
the measure would authorize the fda to debar anyone the agency 
considered a threat to the integrity of the agencys product review 
process and to refuse to review or approve any products submitted 
by a debarred company 
also the fda would be able to withdraw improperly approved 
products and could suspend for two years approvals of other 
products granted to a debarred company during the period when 
illegal activity occurred 
the fda also could impose fines in cases of bribery fraud or 
other illegal acts committed during an fda productapproval 
process under the legislation 
under current law the fda can only ask a drug manufacturer to 
remove a product from the market unless the product is a threat to 
public health otherwise the agency must go through the courts to 
remove a product if a company refuses a request for a recall 
rep john dingell dmich and the chairman of the house energy 
and commerce subcommittee that uncovered much of the evidence of 
fraud and abuse in the generic drug scandal said the legislation 
is well intentioned but were going to continue working on our 
own 
one source who spoke on the condition of anonymity said the 
administrations proposal presents practical difficulties in 
winning passage this year because it is so sweeping affecting 
anyone whose product requires fda approval 
</TEXT>
