<TEXT>
the longest prison siege in british 
history ended wednesday when the last five inmates at strangeways 
prison abandoned their rooftop stronghold 
the five prisoners gingerly walked down the slippery slate roof 
and stepped into a hydraulic lift that carried them the 150 feet 
down to the prison courtyard where they were taken into custody 
the surrender was shown live on the british broadcasting corps 
main evening newscast 
prisoners had taken over the grim overcrowded victorian prison 
in a riot that began april 1 during sunday chapel services about 
300 prisoners overwhelmed guards took the jail keys and released 
the rest of the inmates 
running battles raged in the prison in northern england for 
about four days and prompted unrest and violence in jails 
throughout the country 
in the weeks of negotiations that followed inmates complained 
about conditions in the prison where they had been held three or 
four to a tiny cell allowed a shower and change of clothes once a 
week and provided with a bucket instead of a toilet 
during the siege inmates built and rebuilt barricades and 
planted booby traps to keep out authorities but nearly all of the 
1650 prisoners had surrendered by the time more than 100 officers 
in riot gear moved in wednesday morning 
the final five holdouts were trapped on the roof and a sixth 
inmate was captured in the sweep 
home office spokesman mike gander said prison guards were going 
through the scorched and wrecked jail to search for bodies 
we are confident there are no bodies to be found gander 
said 
one prisoner died as a result of injuries in the riot and one 
prison officer died in the hospital during the riot because of an 
existing heart condition another was slightly injured when the 
facility was being retaken wednesday 
home office minister david mellor on wednesday rejected 
criticism of the authorities strategy of drawnout negotiations 
with the inmates 
would you prefer that wed knocked them off the roof and 
