<TEXT>
dexter gordon walked out on the stage at avery 
fisher hall a tall man with a devilish smile whose body bent with 
a sickly gait 
he plugged his horn between his lips and blew reedy dreams 
and when he was done he accepted the applause but not alone 
when dexter bowed he always stepped back and gave the stage to his 
star his tenor saxophone he had a way of presenting it to the 
audience like a sacred offering to a very special priesthood 
dexter keith gordon had come home 14 years after he left the 
prejudices and restrictions of his homeland for europe 
a man of musical genius and personal humility he died wednesday 
at the age of 67 of kidney failure 
like bb king and his sweet lucille gordons saxophone was 
always his muchappreciated costar with it he helped define and 
refine an important musical legacy bebop 
as the last of this centurys great saxophone geniuses lester 
young charlie parker john coltrane gordon had a reputation as a 
strikingly original jazz soloist the style he developed had a 
strong influence on younger saxophonists of the 60s and 70s and 
is influential even today 
but as important as he was to jazz he never placed himself 
before the music the bebop he championed may have been brash but 
gordon wasnt he embraced humility 
one of my greatest compliments came in 1982 when he said i was 
his favorite guitarist said kenny burrell 
he was an amazing personality he was a good person said 
drummer art blakey who had played with gordon back in the 40s 
with billy eckstines band id see him and id say come on up 
here and stand by my big cymbal dont just be a silent movie 
star 
there was nothing silent about his horn what he spun out was 
the stuff of which dreams were made and gordon was a dream 
merchant of sorts 
listen to the breathy sax pulls on the moody ballad who can 
you turn to or the sensual underpinnings and samba chases of 
manha de carnaval fingerpop and toetap to the cool 
smoothness of coppin the haven enjoy the lively cool of 
tanya 
he was something else he had a style of his own blakey 
said 
gordon came along at a time when the icon of the tenor sax was 
lester young whose lyrical style was the starting point for 
upandcoming horn players including charlie parker but gordon 
carved a new approach for the tenor sax and influenced many of 
youngs proteges john coltrane stan getz sonny stitt 
gordon assimilated parkers musical inventions and added his own 
furious harmonics and multitextured tones sonny rollins and 
coltrane used gordons style as a base and created their own years 
later gordon updated his own sound by learning from them 
dexter gordon was one of the pioneers of the modern 
saxophone burrell said his distinct and very personal style 
plus his strong knowledge of music caused him to be both an 
influential figure among saxophonists and an inspiration to many 
other musicians 
gordon at an early age went to jazz concerts with his father 
who was duke ellington and lionel hamptons doctor when he was 13 
he became to study music theory and clarinet at 15 he switched to 
alto sax studying with lloyd reese who had taught the 
bassistcomposerpianist charles mingus two years later gordon 
was performing in night clubs on tenor sax 
he traveled a rough and craggy road there was booze lots of 
it there were too many drugs there was jail 
but the anguish with which he lived in no way diminished the 
sweetness that came from his saxophone nor did it intrude upon his 
unblinking love of jazz 
when he was nominated for an academy award in 1987 as best actor 
for his portrayal of a tragic jazz musician in bertrand taverniers 
round midnight gordon responded to the news like a high school 
jock whod been made quarterback he had been watching the 
today show with his wife maxine and his stepson while on 
vacation in cuernavaca mexico 
there were giggles and oneword punctuations wow yeah awright 
the film was dedicated to bud powell and i broadened that 
concept to include ben webster coleman hawkins and people like 
that who were expatriates including myself he said at the time 
in an interview with the associated press 
thats why i broadened the character as much as i could to 
touch as many people as possible i wanted to open up my world to 
them and make them aware of all the giants and unsung heros of the 
past they werent aware of 
</TEXT>
