the monthold administration of president fernando collor de 
mello trying to slash hyperinflation and a huge government 
deficit already has drastically limited bank withdrawals and plans 
to sell billions of dollars worth of publicly owned businesses 
secretary of administration joao santana said the reforms made 
out of economic necessity will save brazil 860 million this year 
however it is only half the cuts collor promised during his 
campaign 
santana told a news conference the government identified 11354 
workers holding more than one public job accounting for 25740 
federal positions 
they will have 30 days to justify their situation or lose at 
least one of their jobs he said 
santana said the government expected to save 34 million a month 
by doing away with double jobholding bonuses for top employees 
and highsecurity job categories 
the reforms are the most radical in brazils history they are 
aimed at reducing a bloated inefficient bureaucracy and cutting 
expenses considered largely responsible for brazils 2700 percent 
inflation last year 
santana who is in charge of the reform program also said 23 
state companies were being eliminated and 12000 workers with less 
than five years on the job would be fired 
congress has approved the cuts 
brazil has more than 700000 federal employees a new 
constitution enacted in 1988 gives workers job stability after five 
years 
the government also announced the sale of nine mansions and 
9391 apartments that were reserved for ministers and high 
functionaries as well as 2500 cars and planes tugboats and 350 
dredges 
santana said the money saved could pay for 87000 lowcost 
houses or pay the salaries of 151775 teachers or 88000 doctors 
but he added the government must eliminate its budget 
deficit and these funds will enter the national treasury to cover 
gaps 
the savings from the austerity measures still are far below what 
collor promised when he took office mar 15 he predicted spending 
cuts of 175 billion equal to about 2 percent of brazils 350 
billion gross domestic product 
the next step in the governments plan is a national 
privatization program that calls for the sale of many of brazils 
188 state companies which have a combined debt of 62 billion 
the brazilian congress has authorized the sale of most 
government companies except for the oil monopoly petrobras the 
postal service the telecommunications giant embratel development 
banks and the bank of brazil the countrys largest commercial bank 
foreign capital can acquire only 49 percent of stock in 
privatized companies and 33 percent of voting capital 
