<TEXT>
the st louis sun which hoped to be the first 
major metropolitan newspaper to make a successful launch in this 
country since world war ii unexpectedly folded wednesday after 
only seven months 
at a news conference ralph ingersoll ii editor in chief of the 
new newspaper said the st louis sun had published its last 
edition tuesday night 
closing the sun was a decision the st louis marketplace made 
for us said ingersoll who is also chairman and chief executive 
officer of princeton njbased ingersoll publications co since 
launching the sevenday morning tabloid sept 25 1989 the 
newspaper had published 213 editions 
it is clear that we could not achieve sufficient circulation 
to make this enterprise viable and so we have concluded that there 
is no longer room in st louis for a third newspaper in addition to 
our own suburban journals and the postdispatch ingersoll said 
the sun struggled to overcome higherthanexpected costs 
revolvingdoor circulation limited advertising and a murky image 
the newspaper also had troubles developing everyday readers 
the decision to stop the presses was made sunday ingersoll 
said but apparently few people knew until hours before the news 
conference 
he said the closure which will cost 194 employees their jobs 
stemmed from a failure to build singlecopy sales through vending 
machines and retail outlets and wasnt based on any pressure from 
advertisers or investors 
it had nothing to do with money youll have to take my word 
for it ingersoll said it had to do with single copy sales 
the sun is owned by ingersoll newspapers which owns 77 other 
papers and is part of ralph ingersoll iis newspaper holdings 
on april 1 the newspaper had a circulation of 109000 up from 
a low of 80000 during the winter aided by the start of a new 
bingo promotion ingersoll had guaranteed advertisers 
circulation of 105000 for the first six months of 1990 
the sun also was criticized by some as sensationalizing stories 
for its coverage of a politician involved in a sexual assault and 
of the fiveyear anniversary of an accident in which a man was 
nearly sawed in two 
the newspaper was further chided for running photos of new 
womens swimsuits and lingerie 
but the sun was praised for its coverage of the effort to build 
a new domed stadium downtown and of the troubles facing st louis 
major air carrier trans world airlines 
