<DOCNO> AP900425-0219 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
need cash fast borrow from yourself and pay 
no interest 
however strange that comeon may sound the proposition it 
embodies can be workable for someone who has accumulated a nest egg 
in an individual retirement account 
but beware like many other types of shortterm emergency 
financing it can be a tightrope walk that imposes severe penalties 
if you take a misstep 
the rules governing iras make it clear that the government 
didnt intend these longterm savings vehicles as any source of 
readily available credit 
they state expressly that if you borrow from an ira or even if 
you pledge money in your account as collateral on a loan you will 
be considered to have made a withdrawal subject to taxes 
for people who have not yet reached age 59 that usually means 
a 10 percent penalty tax in addition to any regular income tax 
obligations you incur 
elsewhere in the dense tangle of ira regulations however there 
is a loophole of sorts that permits people of any age to tap their 
accounts once a year for nointerest loans lasting up to 60 
days 
when you do this you technically do not borrow the money at 
all instead you withdraw it from an account with one custodian to 
roll it over into another with a time limit of no more than 60 
days from the date when you receive the money from the first 
custodian 
before your time runs out what you do with the money is up to 
you buy a car take some speculative fling whatever you wish 
of course if you want to preserve your hardearned ira savings 
and avoid costly tax bills you need to be very sure that you will 
be able to pay yourself back in time 
the device of borrowing from an ira should only be 
considered in situations where it is clear that the funds will be 
available to complete the rollover within the 60day period says 
the research institute of america in a current bulletin on the 
subject 
the institute suggests that it may not be assurance enough to 
simply have what businesses call an account receivable a payment 
somebody owes you that may or may not come in on schedule 
theoretically at least you could take your ira money to the 
bank and buy a 58day certificate of deposit pocketing whatever 
interest the cd earns and then put the principal amount back in a 
new ira 
but if the banks payment to you got held up for just three days 
or so because the mail wasnt delivered or the computer went down 
youd be out of luck the irs takes the position that the time 
limit is a time limit leaving little or no room for excuses or 
exceptions 
this iratocdtoira deal would also have a couple of other 
angles you might want to take into account 
first of all the cd interest unlike investment income earned 
in an ira would be subject to current taxation secondly while 
you had the use of the money it wouldnt be earning anything at 
all for your ira savings 
on top of all that while avoiding taxes in an ira rollover you 
could incur other costs such as withdrawal fees at the old 
custodian or setup fees at the new one that would work against any 
net benefit to you 
considering all the pitfalls involved many ira savers might be 
reluctant ever to plan an actual rollover to get at their cash at 
the same time however they might view it as a nice cushion to 
have in reserve 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900425-0220 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
