<TEXT>
much of the world plans reductions in military 
spending but singapore a thriving citystate with no apparent 
enemies is building more bomb shelters 
about 200 shelters and the same number of air raid sirens will 
be completed in the next year and singapore should be ready for its 
first nationwide drill in 1992 home minister shanmugam jayakumar 
said 
the more shelters the better he declared this will mean 
more protection for the public 
protection from what 
southeast asia has been among the worlds more stable regions 
recently but government leaders insist security remains a problem 
despite the improvement in ussoviet relations 
that will not change even if the superpowers reduce their 
military forces in the region said lee hsien loong 37 eldest son 
of prime minister lee kuan yew 
lee addressed parliament as second defense minister he also has 
the trade and industry portfolio and is widely viewed as a future 
prime minister 
if the united states significantly cuts back its military 
forces in the region this will not be a signal for singapore also 
to reduce our forces he said it will be reason for concern 
over a potentially destabilizing change in the regional balance of 
power 
singapore is the only country in the region that openly backs 
continued us military presence officials in several other 
capitals express private support and public nonalignment 
except for singapore the nations of southeast asia think the 
american security shield will stand forever regardless of what 
they do said rep patricia schroeder leader of a house armed 
services committee delegation that toured the area recently 
they can boast of their nonaligned purity while reaping the 
harvest made possible by the american military the colorado 
democrat said 
if the united states cannot renew the leases on philippine bases 
and is forced to leave it will need help from friends in the 
region she said singapore has offered greater access to its air 
and naval facilities 
in his speech to parliament lee said the government would not 
cut defense spending reduce the armed forces or end compulsory 
military training whatever the united states did 
singapore is about the size of chicago with no natural 
resources except a strategic location between the pacific and 
indian oceans and the skills of its 26 million people 76 percent 
of whom are ethnic chinese 
the army navy and air force have 55000 regulars and conscripts 
plus about 200000 reservists analysts rate the singapore armed 
forces among the best trained and equipped in the region 
because it is so small singapore often holds major military 
exercises in brunei taiwan or elsewhere 
it conducts bilateral maneuvers with other members of the 
association of southeast asian nations indonesia malaysia 
thailand brunei and the philippines but asean as a whole does 
not function as a military alliance 
no other asean country is slashing its defense expenditures 
demobilizing its armed forces or acting on the assumption that it 
no longer faces any external threats lee told parliament it 
would be foolhardy for singapore to do so alone 
diplomats from asean countries said the countries awaited 
resolution of two regional problems the search for a peace formula 
in cambodia and negotiations on the us bases 
singapore is in the five power defense agreement with australia 
britain malaysia and new zealand the 1971 pact provides for 
consultation and cooperation among members if singapore or malaysia 
is attacked or threatened 
defense spending is about 6 percent of singapores gross 
national product which means the equivalent of 19 billion in the 
current budget 
us defense spending in 1988 was 61 percent of the gross 
national product or 2931 billion 
some defense funds go to a domestic arms industry that has grown 
so fast it now seeks export orders and diversification 
it was started less than 20 years ago and includes more than 40 
companies under the singapore technologies umbrella the 
governmentbacked companies evolved from making small arms under 
license to designing howitzers and upgrading jet fighters 
singapores total defense plan was drafted in 1983 while 
vietnamese military forces occupied cambodia and aims to involve 
the civilian population with the military in a national emergency 
the first air raid drill sent 3000 volunteers swarming into a 
new subway station in 1988 
nine underground stations have been fortified to shelter 100000 
people shelters also are being built in schools hospitals and 
other public facilities 
other civil defense training covers rescue methods blood 
donation mobilization of private motor vehicles and emergency 
distribution of food and water 
