<TEXT>
fisherprices illfated attempt to broaden its 
line of toys is a textbook case of how a company can get into 
trouble by ignoring its basic business in a drive to expand 
analysts say 
fisherprices troubles became too much for quaker oats co the 
food company said tuesday it would spin off its toy division to 
shareholders 
quaker also reported a 60 percent drop in its fiscal third 
quarter net income the results included a 25 million operating 
loss at fisherprice 
consumers long have associated the fisherprice name with 
sturdy simple imaginative toys for preschoolers 
but the companys attempts to transfer that name recognition to 
toys aimed at older children did not work out well said john g 
taylor who follows the toy industry for lh alton amp co a san 
francisco brokerage 
they took their eye off their basic business taylor said 
that enabled hasbros playskool division rubbermaids little tikes 
division and mattels disneycharacter toys to make inroads into 
fisherprices traditional market 
fisherprices electronic car and electronic guitar two 
products introduced in 1989 reportedly hit production snags that 
delayed shipments to stores in the critical months before 
christmas hurting their sales 
and in the hitdriven toy industry a pricey product that fails 
to live up to expectations can have severe repercussions 
if you lose your focus on your staple predictable product 
line you can get into real trouble if your hit toys turn out to be 
not such big hits after all said analyst carol i palmer at duff 
amp phelps inc in chicago 
fisherprice remains the worlds largest maker of infant and 
preschool toys such as the pullatune xylophone and the little 
people farm 
but fierce competition and its costly attempts to expand have 
cost it millions of dollars and precious market share points 
still taylor said the company has a potent name 
people will say im going to buy a fisherprice toy he 
said thats a unique kind of thing to have 
if they can focus on reinforcing that reputation for quality 
and play value that theyve had in the past they ought to be able 
to get back on track 
quaker chairman william d smithburg said fisherprice should 
fare better as an independent publicly owned company 
in the long term a fisherprice which is not part of a larger 
company should be a more focused organization which should enhance 
its competitiveness and facilitate the attraction retention and 
motivation of its management and employees smithburg said in a 
statement 
quakers stock rose 62 cents to 4925 a share tuesday in 
composite trading on the new york stock exchange 
chicagobased quaker had been rumored for several months to be 
considering selling fisherprice which posted an 11 percent 
decline in operating income in fiscal 1989 and last month closed a 
