president bush is dismissing a prediction that 
his proposed cutbacks in farm program payments would cause a 
financial crisis in agriculture 
the president reacted tuesday to concerns raised by sen bob 
kerrey dneb who wants the senate agriculture committee to 
approve price supports of 12 billion a year for five years under 
the 1990 farm bill 
kerrey said farm economy has improved considerably since the 
early 1980s 
however he told a meeting of the national association of 
agricultural journalists if you dont provide this level of 
funding in two years you are going to see this recovery vanish 
there are many things i respect about senator kerrey said 
bush told the same group later in the day sometimes we have a 
philosophical difference of opinion i have a different view on 
this 
bush is seeking 102 billion in price supports for fiscal 1991 
which begins oct 1 his proposals envision further cuts in 
government support over the years and more prosperity for farmers 
in the open market 
but kerrey said failed farming operations brought on by 
insufficient government support would cost more taxpayer money in 
the long run than the annual 12 billion he is advocating 
