<TEXT>
an environmentalist group briefly disrupted the 
exxon corp annual meeting today while executives told shareholders 
the alaskan shore slimed with oil from the exxon valdez should be 
cleaned by summers end 
very substantial progress has obviously been made exxon 
president lee r raymond said in detailing the cleanup of the worst 
oil spill in us history now a rallying cry for the environmental 
movement 
raymond cited a massive summerlong effort last year the 
scouring of winter storms and the application last fall of a 
fertilizer to speed the biological decay of the oil 
in contrast with the roughly 250 demonstrators who attended last 
years annual meeting in new jersey about 20 people outside 
todays gathering carried signs urging a boycott of exxon products 
but later inside while exxon executives spoke they were 
interrupted when jay hair president of the national wildlife 
federation took issue with the upbeat review of exxons alaska 
operations 
we call that bull he said suggesting the damage goes 
beyond the environment listen to the people of alaska whose 
lives have been destroyed and youre putting the profits in your 
pockets hair said to loud boos from the audience 
exxon has come under harsh criticism from environmentalists 
politicians and many shareholders for what was perceived as its 
inadequate response to the alaska disaster the worst oil spill in 
us history 
the meeting agenda was dominated by the 11 milliongallon spill 
which occurred march 24 1989 when the tanker exxon valdez hit a 
reef shareholders were scheduled to vote on six environmentally 
related resolutions 
some environmental groups also have called informally for 
chairman lawrence g rawl to resign although he is not expected to 
do so 
demonstrators handed out leaflets suggesting 10 questions 
shareholders should ask exxon management about its response to the 
oil spill and other problems 
once inside the george r brown convention center shareholders 
passed through metal detectors and then passed through an elaborate 
display called progress in alaska detailing exxons cleanup 
efforts in prince william sound 
some of the criticism against exxon has been over its decision 
to reduce activity last september in preparation for alaskas harsh 
winter one display told shareholders that nature takes over the 
cleaning job with intense storm activity during the fall winter 
and spring 
exxon executives said the company will resume fullscale cleanup 
within a few weeks after a survey is completed of remaining damage 
spokesman henry w beathard estimated the job would be finished by 
the end of summer 
rawl and raymond each touted exxons environmental efforts 
during remarks opening the meeting attended by more than 1000 
shareholders 
in addition to reaffirming our own commitment to safety and 
environmental protection exxon has been an active participant in 
the development of guiding principles for the petroleum and 
chemical industries rawl said 
the company had spent some 2 billion for spillrelated expenses 
through the end of 1989 and faces possible further costs for civil 
and criminal damages linked to the disaster and other oil spills 
the environmentrelated shareholder resolutions include pledges 
by exxon to reduce its emissions of pollutants and toxic waste 
create a special environmental affairs committee on its board of 
directors and follow the socalled valdez principles for corporate 
environmental conduct 
exxon says all the resolutions are duplicative and unnecessary 
and should be rejected by shareholders 
also today exxon said it would join other oil companies in 
reformulating some of its gasolines to burn cleaner exxon said it 
would market its gasolines in 40 markets in the east and along the 
gulf coast exxon will sell the reformulated gasoline in the new 
york area yearround and in other areas during the summer 
