here is a brief history of the retailer 
the idea for what has become the saks chain originated with 
horace saks and bernard gimbel who independently operated stores 
in new york city in the early part of this century the two 
merchants decided to open a fashionable specialty department store 
catering to affluent customers the store on fifth avenue opened 
sept 15 1924 
from 1924 to 1969 saks expanded and built a national 
recognition as an upscale retailer mainly of higher priced apparel 
bernard gimbels cousin adam became president after the 
sudden death of horace saks in 1926 under adam gimbel branch 
stores were opened and the flagship manhattan store was redecorated 
in the opulent art moderne style from the 1925 paris exposition 
adam gimbel retired as saks president in 1969 at the time 
there were 21 saks stores 
saks in 1973 was bought by batus inc the us holding 
company of the londonbased conglomerate bat industries plc 
under bats ownership saks has grown to include 45 stores 
operating in 30 major markets in 20 states states in which there 
are saks stores include arizona california connecticut florida 
georgia illinois louisana maryland massachusetts michigan 
minnesota missouri nevada new jersey new york oklahoma 
pennsylvania texas and virginia a 46th store in houston that has 
performed poorly is being closed while three new saks are to be 
opened by the end of 1990 
the flagship fifth avenue store was proclaimed a new york city 
landmark in 1965 
bat announced in september 1989 plans to sell saks its sister 
retailing operations plus certain other assets as part of a 
strategy to thwart an unsolicited takeover attempt by an investment 
group led by the anglofrench financier sir james goldsmith the 
group on april 23 dropped its 22 billion bid but bat said it would 
continue its restructuring and asset sales 
saks management announced march 15 1990 that it had submitted 
a bid for the chain the buyout proposal was made jointly with tobu 
department store co ltd of japan 
the sale of its breuners furniture retail and rental 
subsidiaries were announced by bat on march 27 and april 2 
respectively negotiations continue for the sale of iveys a 
specialty department store chain with 23 stores in the carolinas 
and florida 
bat announced on april 19 that it had agreed to sell saks 
sister retailer chicagobased marshall field amp co to dayton 
hudson corp for 104 billion 
bat on april 25 announced it has accepted a bid of 15 
billion for saks from investcorp an international investment bank 
with a wide range of retail and other holdings the bid was one of 
a handful of final proposals for the chain 
in commenting on its acquisition investcorp said it will keep 
all existing saks stores open for business and will carry on 
current expansion and renovation plans benefits for saks 
employees will be continued at current levels 
paul soldatos a member of investcorps management committee 
that led the effort to buy saks said the group relies on 
professional managers to run businesses he said in an interview 
that investcorp will meet with saks management as soon as possible 
to discuss the future he said no meeting had taken place yet 
because saks management had been competing in the auction 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

