<TEXT>
far from the boardroom battles between 
carl icahn and usx corp over the bottom line on steel the steel 
valley is bottoming out 
this towns mammoth mill forged the locks for the panama canal 
the girders for the golden gate bridge the beams for the empire 
state building the wheels for disneyland rides and the armor plate 
that crushed hitler and hirohito 
but after more than a century of steelmaking it was shuttered 
in 1986 as part of a corporate overhaul it is an icon of the 
smokestack age and a way of life extinct 
about 9000 people were employed here a decade ago wreckers 
toil at the homestead works now like scavengers picking innards of 
a carcass 
the last of five generations of steelworkers who witnessed the 
demolition talk caustically about wall street raiders and corporate 
revamping 
ninetynine out of 100 people who lost their jobs see it as 
the wrangling between two sharks who have already eaten them 
said mike stout 40 an exsteelworker who runs a printing shop 
they are extremely bitter they feel betrayed they want nothing 
to do with us steel ever again 
icahn usxs largest shareholder with 133 percent of its stock 
sees steel as a drain on the companys marathon oil co and texas 
oil and gas corp 
last year energy accounted for 65 percent of business for usx 
which changed its name from us steel four years ago and remains 
the nations largest steelmaker ten years ago steel was 70 
percent of sales 
icahn envisions a separate entity called us steel co of 
which 80 percent would be peddled to usx shareholders usx 
executives oppose the idea though they agreed to hold a nonbinding 
shareholder vote may 7 
but to the laborers who once felt the open hearth furnaces cook 
through their steeltoed shoes splitting the company would be a 
meaningless formality for them the furnaces are no longer an 
eternal flame 
people sort of accept it as fact that us steel is going to 
be chopped up said bob anderson a former steelworker who runs 
homesteads rainbow kitchen a food job and clothing bank 
theyve already dismembered the plants now theyre going to 
dismember the corporation anderson said it could be the final 
nail in the coffin the death of a way of life its not the steel 
valley anymore were an industrial graveyard 
as proof of changing times a fantasylike oasis has sprouted 
amid the ashes the sandcastle amusement park beckons visitors with 
water slides sandy beach and wooden boardwalk it adjoins the 
bankrupt mesta machine corp once the worlds largest maker of 
steelmaking equipment 
the region was called steel valley because hulking mills 
sprouted along the monongahela river south of pittsburgh the river 
network and direct access to coal fields made it an ideal place for 
steel basic metal of the 20th century 
the valley also was the backbone of us steel the worlds 
first billion dollar corporation some of capitalisms wealthiest 
barons forged the company out of a 1901 debtfinanced megadeal that 
was the biggest acquisition in history up to that point in todays 
dollars the 14 billion deal would be worth about 23 billion and 
would dwarf most of todays mergers 
the centerpiece was andrew carnegies mills in the steel valley 
which merged with seven other steel companies and john 
rockefellers iron mines through jp morgans financing 
the company prospered so did legions of slavs poles italians 
irish and german immigrant laborers drawing steady paychecks to 
raise families 
but the raw and brutal work had a price the whistles hisses 
rumbles the stench of sulphur eyesores of slag heaps rivers that 
ran like industrial sewers and air so dirty it blotted out the sun 
while street lights burned in the afternoon 
today renaissance pittsburgh is a corporate center with a 
gleaming skyline servicebased industry clean air and rivers 
rand mcnally rated it the nations most liveable place in 1986 and 
it is now ranked third 
but in steels heyday muckraking author lincoln steffens 
recoiled at the belching furnaces and called the area hell with 
the lid off 
when asked how the city could spruce itself up in the 1940s 
architect frank lloyd wright said abandon it 
back then us steel was more than just a job or a profitloss 
statement it was a paternal entity that dominated local politics 
determined land use paid most of the taxes and built libraries 
gyms and music halls 
the company and its predecessors also had their own security 
hired guns often battled union organizers in 1892 10 people were 
killed and scores injured when 300 armed pinkerton guards fired on 
strikers at carnegies homestead works 
us steel fused with all aspects of life even the sporting and 
spiritual its logo adorns the helmets of pittsburghs pro football 
team the steelers a stained glass window in a homestead church 
pictures steel being poured 
everybody in one way or another depended on us steel it was 
everybodys safety net said jo debolt director of the steel 
industry heritage task force which hopes to salvage part of the 
cadaver of homestead works as a museum 
imagine spending your whole life doing something youre proud 
of and all at once its gone people lost their sense of place if 
you live in the steel valley and you dont make steel anymore what 
are you mrs debolt said 
the safety net disintegrated in the 1980s failure to modernize 
sweetheart labor deals and imports contributed to the collapse 
steel valley became the symbolic capital of the rust bowl 
in 1979 26000 people worked for us steel in the valley 
today about 4000 toil at three remaining plants 
the only steelmaking plant is the edgar thomson works built in 
1875 as carnegies first mill he named it for the president of the 
pennsylvania railroad the biggest customer of carnegies rails 
the overhaul made usx leaner and meaner it takes less time and 
labor costs to make steel but it came with a social cost usx sold 
or closed 15 plants or mining operations in the past 10 years 
including homestead 
overall the region around steel valley lost 100000 
manufacturing jobs and 30 percent of its population workers sought 
jobs elsewhere in the biggest industrial dislocation of the decade 
for those who stayed the main industry became survival 
a survey sponsored last year by the united steelworkers of 
america showed 40 percent of the workers remain jobless those who 
found work take home 40 percent to 68 percent less than their steel 
wages 
to help allegheny county mental health created a program called 
bridge to recovery in 1986 it is run by lois brown 40 an 
exsteelworker whose father worked 40 years in a steel mill and 
whose grandfather worked in a tin mill her daughter works for usx 
for many of the people affected its too painful to think 
about this was a way of life almost from the beginning of time 
now theres nothing left its like it never existed mrs brown 
said 
still for many remaining usx workers the battle with icahn is 
worrisome although they have no love for usx and still smart from 
a sixmonth lockout four years ago the hard hats tend to align 
themselves with the company 
we know usx wed rather deal with the devil than the 
unknown said gary hubbard of the usw whose ranks have declined 
to 700000 half its alltime peak 
we are very much opposed to mergers and acquisitions for no 
other purpose than to saddle healthy companies with a huge debt 
burden he said the workers always pay the price 
the jitters are worst among those working at the remnants of 
steel valley 
the bombs are going to go off barney oursler of the mon 
valley unemployed committee said of the corporate haggling all 
they can hope for is they can duck so they dont get killed in the 
explosion 
