<TEXT>
he can strike fear deep into the hearts of the 
most financially acrobatic state and municipal treasurers because 
of his power to shape the bottom lines of their budgets 
hyman c grossman who evaluates their fiscal health for 
standard amp poors corp demonstrated that clout last month when he 
told new yorks budget makers he didnt like the states numbers 
the influential rating agency downgraded new yorks credit standing 
the move jolted new yorks byzantine budget process causing 
republicans and democrats alike to repent for years of effective 
deficit spending and work toward a true balanced budget 
the sudden conversion to the cause of fiscal probity didnt come 
cheap the rating move is expected to cost the states taxpayers 
180 million in higher debt interest payments over the next four 
years 
someone once called us a fourth branch of government 
grossman says its not a label he likes though he stresses that 
the agency tries to keep its distance from public officials to 
guarantee a dispassionate view of government finances 
were an important link in moving financing from the 
government to the ultimate investor really grossman says 
were kind of an umpire weve got to call it as we see it 
grossman constantly speaks in the plural voice emphasizing that 
he doesnt sit alone behind the plate the companys municipal 
department has 120 analysts and every major borrower is reviewed 
by a committee of at least five people 
a major rating change has to be pretty close to unanimous 
he says 
but as managing director of criteria and rating policy he sets 
the pace for the department he also chairs the rating committees 
for several key borrowers including new york state and city new 
jersey florida and texas 
grossman 55 has been making calls on state and local 
government finances for 27 years at sampp hes seen everything from 
the near bankruptcy of new york city in the mid1970s to the big 
state surpluses of the mid 80s to the shortfalls currently 
plaguing many state treasurers particularly in the northeast 
he says the pressures facing the states today are serious the 
federal government has cut back sharply on aid for social services 
transportation and water treatment 
at the same time sluggish economies have curbed the growth of 
income and sales tax revenues and corporate taxes arent picking 
up the slack 
the debtfinanced takeover boom of the 1980s has hurt state 
coffers by substituting taxdeductible debt for equity the record 
25 billion buyout of rjr nabisco for example probably will cost 
north carolina 100 million in lost income this year one quarter 
of its budget shortfall grossman says 
as new york state seeks to cope with a projected 15 billion 
shortfall grossman has suggested the state consider an income tax 
surcharge but he dismisses the idea that sampp tries to dictate 
policy 
were not necessarily advocates of higher taxes or lower taxes 
or more or less spending but we are advocates of credible and 
balanced financial operations he says 
theres a fine line between dictating specific policies and 
pushing for change though grossman was well aware of the 
political impact of a rating change when his team voted to 
downgrade new york after repeatedly expressing concern about the 
states accumulated deficits and a yawning budget gap for the 
latest fiscal year 
frankly if you express concern concern concern and you keep 
the rating you dont change policy and we felt that policy needed 
to be changed not that were dictating policy but the only way 
attention could be called to this credit deterioration was to 
change the rating 
the decision dropped the states rating by two notches to 
singlea the third lowest among the states after lowly louisiana 
and massachusetts telephoning state officials with the news was 
not easy but its part of our job grossman says 
budget director dall w forsythe said the state was surprised by 
the twonotch drop and that sampp didnt wait until legislators and 
the executive had agreed on a budget package 
we disagree on some of their judgments and decisions he 
said but he didnt challenge grossmans expertise he is a very 
knowledgeable professional he says 
rating governments is a natural for grossman who has a lifelong 
interest in public policy 
a new york city native grossman studied political science at 
new york university and became active in local democratic politics 
he spent one year in law school but left to marry in 1960 and earn 
a living on wall street 
he served as council president in his hometown of marlboro 
township in the new jersey suburbs from 1977 to 1981 the council 
agreed at the outset not to seek a rating from sampp if it borrowed 
during the period which it didnt 
as a member of the governmental accounting standards advisory 
council grossman is helping to revise accounting guidelines for 
public bodies across the country 
assessing the creditworthiness of a state or municipality is 
more complex and subjective than rating a corporation grossman 
says you cant just look at widget sales and debt payment 
schedules the rater has to judge the political process that 
produces the budget 
you develop a credibility assessment of the government youre 
dealing with grossman says in new yorks case years of 
papering over the deficit with oneshot financing deals wore 
credibility too thin he says 
grossman also emphasizes the strength or weakness of an areas 
underlying economy something forsythe says distinguishes sampp from 
its chief rival moodys investors service grossman doesnt like 
computer models though he relies on his nose for anecdotal 
evidence 
on a trip to austin texas for example he dropped into a real 
estate brokers office and was startled to find the office vacancy 
rate was 38 percent hardly a robust indicator 
two weeks before last christmas he took a lunchtime tour of a 
half dozen of manhattans most exclusive jewelry and department 
stores talking to salespeople to assess the consumer mood 
i said tell me hows business well mr grossman were 
not supposed to talk about this but this is the worst christmas 
weve had in seven years he recalled them saying 
for grossman that was a sure sign the recession in the areas 
financial services industry would give the city and state a double 
whammy crimping income and sales tax revenues 
to treasurers making decisions that affect millions of 
taxpayers that may seem a flippant way to forecast but grossman 
trusts his methods calling them informal but very reliable 
thats just the kind of confidence youd expect in an umpire 
</TEXT>
