<TEXT>
here are short profiles of some of the major 
figures in wall streets financial scandals 
ivan boesky the former speculator in takeover stocks was 
accused of running a broad insider trading network he settled 
charges by paying 100 million and pleading guilty to one count of 
lying to federal regulators he was released from federal custody 
april 4 after completing two years of a threeyear prison term 
michael r milken former head of junkbond trading at drexel 
burnham lambert inc pleaded guilty tuesday to six counts of 
violating federal securities and tax laws and agreed to pay 600 
million he faces up to 28 years in prison at sentencing oct 1 
four of the six charges involved dealings with boesky but none 
were for insider trading or racketeering milken had been charged 
with 98 counts of fraud and racketeering in march 1989 
dennis levine a former managing director at drexel was 
paroled last year after serving 17 months of a twoyear prison term 
for securities fraud tax evasion and perjury levines confessions 
about a broad insider trading ring led prosecutors to boesky 
levine pleaded guilty to four felonies and returned 116 million 
in alleged illegal profits 
martin siegel pleaded guilty in 1987 to illegal stock trading 
and tax evasion while head of mergers and acquisitions at kidder 
peabody amp co he also agreed to return 9 million in cash and 
securities to settle civil charges for his role in illegal dealings 
with boesky siegel a former drexel managing director is awaiting 
sentencing 
boyd l jefferies a los angeles stockbroker snared in the 
boesky web was placed on probation and fined 250000 after two 
years of helping the government he pleaded guilty to two felony 
counts in 1987 and then testified in the trials of gaf corp and 
corporate raider paul bilzerian 
bruce newberg a former drexel trader was indicted with milken 
and convicted with five others in the princetonnewport partners 
racketeering and fraud trial he was sentenced to three months in 
prison in the princetonnewport case newberg was milkens 
assistant at drexels beverly hills calif highyield bond 
division his status in the milken indictment is unresolved 
paul a bilzerian the florida takeover strategist last year 
received four years in prison for his conviction on nine counts of 
securities fraud conspiracy and making false statements and was 
fined 15 million the prison sentence for the former singer co 
chairman was the stiffest in the wall street scandals so far 
bilzerian is is free pending appeal 
robert freeman former head of arbitrage for goldman sachs amp 
co was arrested along with two other executives for insider 
trading implicated by siegel freeman pleaded guilty to one felony 
count and this month was sentenced to four months in prison and 
fined 1 million 
