<TEXT>
precious metal futures prices plunged wednesday as a 
supplyconnected collapse of platinum prices triggered selling in 
the gold and silver markets which had already been weakened by a 
lack of investor demand 
gold for spot delivery traded as low as 370 an ounce for the 
first time since april 2 and silver plummeted to its lowest level 
in nearly four years 
on other commodity markets copper futures surged to an 
eightmonth high oil futures were sharply lower grains and 
soybeans retreated and livestock and meat futures were mixed 
gold futures settled 520 to 570 lower on new yorks 
commodity exchange with the contract for delivery in april at 
37070 a troy ounce silver was 75 cents to 91 cents lower with 
april at 4919 the lowest settlement price for a nearmonth 
silver contract on the exchange since may 19 1986 
platinum futures finished 1560 lower across the board on the 
new york mercantile exchange with july at 47220 a troy ounce the 
lowest nearmonth platinum settlement since april 2 
the tumble extended tuesdays steep losses in gold and silver 
which analysts had attributed mainly to weak investor demand in the 
face of rising interest rates 
waves of selling swept easily through the thinlytraded platinum 
market early in the session amid signs of physical platinum sales 
by the japanese and an announcement by the worlds largest platinum 
producer of plans to increase production beginning in 1991 
analysts agreed the expansion plans by south africas rustenburg 
platinum co may have no effect on supplies of refined platinum for 
several years but because the company is such a large supplier 
its announcement really set us off said james steel a metals 
analyst with the futures brokerage refco inc 
