<TEXT>
the united states and japan reached agreement 
wednesday to expand sales of american wood products as the bush 
administration hinted that japans actions will keep it off a hit 
list of countries with the most offensive trade barriers 
the agreement wrapped up the final outstanding case cited by the 
bush administration a year ago when it targeted tokyo for priority 
marketopening negotiations 
us trade representative carla hills announcing the successful 
conclusion of the talks said the agreement which lowers tariffs 
and revises japanese building code standards should result in a 1 
billion increase in american export sales while providing 
lowercost and higherquality wood housing to japanese 
consumers 
the administration a year ago targeted japan for its barriers to 
sales of american wood products satellites and supercomputers 
all three issues have been settled in the last five weeks after 
months of talks with little progress 
the government of japanese prime minister toshiki kaifu has 
pushed to lower trade tensions between the two economic superpowers 
since president bush and kaifu held a recent trade summit in 
california 
the bush administration faces a monday deadline for deciding 
whether to target japan in a second round of marketopening 
negotiations under a tough section of the 1988 trade law known as 
super 301 
various american industry groups and members of congress argue 
that the administration must cite japan again to keep pressure on a 
country that accounts for nearly half of americas overall trade 
deficit 
but hills while saying the administration has not made its 
final decision strongly indicated that she opposed targeting japan 
again 
she said that in a review of 33 japanese trade barriers she 
could find none that could best be resolved through use of the 
super 301 process that provision provides for retaliatory 
sanctions if the barriers arent removed within a specified period 
of time 
she told the committee that the flurry of concessions made by 
japan in the past month indicated that kaifus government seriously 
intended to resolve trade frictions 
however various senators said tokyos record in honoring past 
agreements was weak and that there was no evidence the latest round 
of commitments would make a dent in americas 49 billion deficit 
with japan 
senate finance committee chairman lloyd bentsen dtexas said 
the administration would be making a serious mistake if it failed 
to target japan under super 301 which he called the cornerstone of 
the 1988 trade law 
he and sen john danforth rmo both held out the threat that 
congress would block approval of pending trade agreements with 
eastern european countries the soviet union and china if the 
administration failed to target japan 
if the administration ignores a trade law that congress has 
constitutionally enacted i am concerned it may poison the well for 
the consideration of those agreements bentsen told hills 
however hills asked the committee to give her more leeway in 
choosing the best way to gain market access with japan 
i need a little of your confidence and just a little longer 
tether she said 
bush and the economic policy group of his cabinet were scheduled 
to hear thursday from hills on the super 301 designation with 
indications that an announcement on the issue could come late 
thursday or friday 
last year the administration cited japan brazil and india for 
the priority negotiations hills said that the discussions with 
japan and brazil had been successful but that no progress had been 
made in talks with india concerning foreign investment and 
insurance 
some in the administration have argued that no country should be 
cited this year but sen john heinz rpa said such a decision 
would send a dangerous and inaccurate message that america is 
not concerned about unfair barriers 
sen don riegle dmich warned hills that he would push for 
legislation to extend the requirement for the administration to 
target countries which was due to expire this year 
if a foreign country thinks they can slide by this year with 
talk and talk we are going to come back and tighten up the law 
riegle said 
however sens bob packwood roregon and daniel patrick 
moynihan dny both said that they feared that targeting japan 
after it had met us demands would be wrong 
</TEXT>
